= Hindenburgs.

As the late summer sun dipped behind the hangars of Berlin-Staaken, the LZ-129 stood as a shimmering silver monument to a Germany that refused to die. Paul von Hindenburg, the eighty-five-year-old Field Marshal and President, gathered the remnants of the Old World for what he privately termed his "Final Vigil."

The mission was ostensibly pragmatic: to secure the final cessation of war reparations and to forge a "Gentleman’s Peace" with France. To the aging President, it was a chance to restore the dignity of the German state—not through the brutal street-policing of Noske’s "Social Fascists," but through the weight of Prussian tradition.

The airship’s passenger lounge was a microcosm of the German Right, a collection of men of the old Prussian order and ways: Hugo Eckener, The master of the air; Franz von Papen and Kurt von Schleicher, two of the bitter rivals of the Cabal. President's son Oskar and for remaining: Media magnate Hugenberg, Schiele and Wultz - Junkers and industrialist Quaatz.

As the ship turned its nose toward the French border, the engines hummed with a deceptive stability...

- @end: Hindenburgs arrive to the Paris...

