= Catastrophy

The structural failure originated in the upper quadrant of the stern, near the horizontal stabilizers. At 21:14 hours, a sudden longitudinal shearing force—likely exacerbated by a localized microburst over the Ardennes—caused a bracing wire to snap. The high-tension wire whipped through the interior of the ship, puncturing a series of hydrogen cells. The resulting leak encountered an electrical arc from a severed lighting circuit.

​The ignition was instantaneous. Because the LZ-129 was inflated with hydrogen rather than helium, the fire did not smolder; it detonated. The silver-doped fabric of the outer hull acted as a massive fuse, carrying the wall of flame forward at a speed that defied the crew's perception. It was last time Hindenburgs were as bright as stars...

In Berlin, the news reached the Wilhelmstraße via a panicked telegram from the French border patrol. Gustav Noske was reportedly woken from his sleep to receive the report. Everyone did. Glorious Marshall was soon to be declared deceased... German people couldn't believe themselves.

Perhaps, it is over?...

- @end_3: What's next?

